❯ so you mean its not chunked response, what do you mean by zero copy

● Correct, it's not chunked transfer encoding. The response uses a fixed Content-Length header — the client knows the exact size upfront and
  receives a single contiguous byte stream.

  ---
  Zero-copy refers to what happens inside the kernel when sendfile() is called.

  Normal file-to-socket transfer (without sendfile):
  disk → kernel page cache → user-space buffer → kernel socket buffer → NIC
                           ↑                   ↑
                      read() copies        write() copies
                      data here            data here
  Two copies cross the kernel/user-space boundary. The data passes through your process's memory even though your code never looks at it.

  With sendfile():
  disk → kernel page cache → kernel socket buffer → NIC
                           ↑
                      kernel moves data
                      internally (no user-space crossing)
  The kernel transfers directly from the file's page cache to the socket buffer without ever copying bytes into your process's address space. Your
  process just makes the syscall and the kernel does the rest.

  The practical effect: for large files, sendfile() is faster and uses less CPU because it avoids those two memory copies. It's the same mechanism
  used by nginx for static file serving.

  The "zero-copy" label is slightly informal — there may still be a DMA copy to the NIC — but from the application's perspective, zero bytes are
  copied through user space.

